es></name></person-group><article-title>Reinfusion of concentrated ascitic fluid versus paracentesis. A randomized prospective trial</article-title><source>Dig Dis Sci</source><year>1997</year><volume>42</volume><fpage>1708</fpage><lpage>1714</lpage><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">9286238</pub-id></element-citation></ref></ref-list></back><floats-group><fig id="F1" orientation="portrait" position="float"><label>Fig. 1</label><caption><p>Clinical course. We began empirical antibiotic therapy with ceftriaxone intravenously (1 g/day). Abdominal paracentesis (3 l/day) and albumin transfusion (25%, 100 ml/day) were performed 6 times, but the effect was temporary, and control of ascites was poor. S-alb decreased to 1.8 g/dl, prerenal failure deteriorated, urinary volume declined, and ascites increased yet further. Because the PMN count in ascites decreased to 58 cells/mm<sup>3</sup> and ascites were also endotoxin negative, CART was initiated, with 3.0 l of ascites filtrated and concentrated to 0.3 l in 120 min. At such time, S-alb rose gradually, and the level of ascites decreased. CART was performed a total of 6 times, and ascites were well controlled, with no observation of fever, hypotension, or other adverse effects. Biochemical results also improved to S-alb 3.2 g/dl and S-Cr 1.2 mg/dl, and the patient was discharged.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="cru-0002-0138-g01"/></fig><table-wrap id="T1" orientation="portrait" position="float"><label>Table 1</label><caption><p>Laboratory findings on admission</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><tbody><tr valign="top"><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Urinalysis</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"/></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02003;&#x02003;Protein</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02013;</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02003;&#x02003;Glucose</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">&#x02013;</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1